    <!-- Translation notes -->
    <h3>Translation notes</h3>
    <p>The Bohr model is historically important but physically wrong: electrons do not orbit like planets. The Schrodinger equation gives probability clouds (orbitals), not orbits. However, the energy levels E_n = -13.6/n^2 eV are exact for hydrogen. Our electron configuration code follows the Aufbau filling order, which has exceptions for chromium (Z=24) and copper (Z=29) due to half-filled subshell stability. The radioactive decay law is exact for large numbers of atoms; individual decays are random.</p>

